Prediction of a Variant being Disease-Related

Introduction

Individual variants were obtained by aligning short sequences belonging to a person with the reference human genome. In this assignment I used variants of a sample patient. Each variant is labeled as â€œPâ€ meaning disease-related and â€œNâ€ for not disease-related. Here is the question that we want to be able to answer after exploring this dataset;
-Prediction: given new variant, how accurate can the model predict their classes (Classification (P or N))?

Data preprocessing

  • Cleaning the data (remove duplicates, deal with missing values, data type conversions,subsetting)
mycols <- c("GeneName","Chr","Start","End","Ref","Alt","Func.refGene","type","VariantQuality","Quality","Depth","Percentage_of_Heterozygosity",
            "Zygosity","Compound_Heterozygous","impact_severity","gnomAD_exome_ALL","1000g2015aug_all",
            "ExAC_ALL","MEDIPOL_TOT_CNT","MEDIPOL_HOMO_CNT","MEDIPOL_HETE_CNT","MEDIPOL_FREQ","CLNSIG","HGMD_classification",
            "Is_ACMG_Gene","InterVar","InterVar_automated","InterVarEvidences","Revel_pred","SIFT_pred","MutationTaster_pred","dann","CADD13_PHRED",
            "GERP++_RS","HGMD_Phenotype","OMIM_ClinicalSynopsis","OMIM_Phenotype","OMIM_Inheritance","HPO_Diseases","HPO_Phenotype") 

mData <- myData[, c(mycols, setdiff(names(myData), mycols))]

mData <- mData[,c(1:which(colnames(mData)=="HPO_Phenotype"))]


hpo <- hpo %>%
  mutate(inf = "yes")


mData <- setDT(mData)[ i = hpo, In_Hpo := i.inf,
                       on = .(Chr,Start,End,Ref,Alt)]

mData <- mData %>%
  mutate(In_Hpo = ifelse(ExAC_ALL >0.01, NA, In_Hpo))
mData <- mData %>%
  mutate(type = ifelse(type == "snp", 0, 1),
         Zygosity = ifelse(Zygosity == "hom alt", 0, 1),
         Compound_Heterozygous = ifelse(Compound_Heterozygous=="yes", 1, 0),
         impact_severity = ifelse(impact_severity == "HIGH", 1,ifelse(impact_severity == "MED",0,-1)),
         Is_ACMG_Gene=ifelse(Is_ACMG_Gene == "no", 0, 1),
         #In_CNV=ifelse(In_CNV == "no", 0, 1),
         Revel_pred = ifelse(Revel_pred == "Likely benign", 1,ifelse(Revel_pred == "Likely disease causing",0,-1)),
         SIFT_pred = ifelse(SIFT_pred == "Tolerated", 1,ifelse(SIFT_pred == "Deleterious",0,-1)),
         MutationTaster_pred = ifelse(MutationTaster_pred == "Disease_causing", 1,ifelse(MutationTaster_pred == "Disease_causing_aotomatic",2,
                              ifelse(MutationTaster_pred == "Polymorphism",3,ifelse(MutationTaster_pred == "Polymorphism_automatic",0,-1)))),
         HGMD_Phenotype=ifelse(HGMD_Phenotype == "No association", 0, 1),
         OMIM_ClinicalSynopsis=ifelse(OMIM_ClinicalSynopsis == "No association", 0, 1),
         OMIM_Phenotype=ifelse(OMIM_Phenotype == "No association", 0, 1),
         OMIM_Inheritance=ifelse(OMIM_Inheritance == "No association", 0, 1),
         HPO_Diseases=ifelse(HPO_Diseases == "No association", 0, 1),
         HPO_Phenotype=ifelse(HPO_Phenotype == "No association", 0, 1),
         In_Hpo=ifelse(is.na(In_Hpo), 0,1))

mData$CADD13_PHRED <- as.double(mData$CADD13_PHRED)
## Warning: Zorlamadan dolayÄ± ortaya Ã§Ä±kan NAs
mData$dann <- as.double(mData$dann)
## Warning: Zorlamadan dolayÄ± ortaya Ã§Ä±kan NAs
mData <- mData %>%
  mutate(Classification=ifelse(((tolower(InterVar_automated) %like% "pathogenic") | 
                        (tolower(InterVar) %like% "pathogenic") | 
                        HGMD_classification != "None" | 
                        (tolower(CLNSIG) %like% "pathogenic")) & In_Hpo == 1 &
                          ExAC_ALL <= 0.01 & gnomAD_exome_ALL <= 0.01 & `1000g2015aug_all` <= 0.01,"P","N"))
mData$Classification <- as.factor(mData$Classification)

mData <- mData %>%
        rowwise() %>% 
        mutate(Variant = paste0(GeneName,"-",Chr,":",Start,"-",End,"-",Ref,"-",Alt))
mData <- mData[,-c(1:7,23,24,26:28)]

mData <- mData[,c(30,29,1:28)]

Creating Training Data Set

#set the seed
set.seed(101)

#creating trainin data (%20 for training)

intrain <- createDataPartition(y = mData$Classification, p= 0.2, list = FALSE)
training <- mData[intrain,-1]
testing <- mData[-intrain,-1]
dim(training); dim(testing);
## [1] 7629   29
## [1] 30510    29
#Create a cross validation object for 10 fold CV with 3 replicates

trctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10,repeats = 3)

Comparision the Algorithms

From the results, it is shown that even with different parameters for each algorithm, most of the accuracy remain unchanged. This is due to the class imbalances. Altough the accuracies are high, the kappa results are mostly 0.

svmRadial(Support Vector Machines with Radial Basis Function Kernel) model with the parameters sigma = 1 and C = 1 gave the highest accuracy (0.9993451). The other algorithms also gave approximate values.

results <- resamples(list(svmRadial=svmRadial, svmLinear=svmLinear, svmPoly=svmPoly,rf=rf,knn=knn,glm=glm))
